LAT101H1-F-20169.courseDescription: An intensive introduction to Latin for students who have no knowledge of the language; preparation for the reading of Latin literature.
LAT101H1-F-20169.exclusion: LAT100Y1. Students who have studied Latin previously must obtain permission from the Undergraduate Coordinator before enrolling.

LAT102H1-S-20169.courseDescription: A continuation of the intensive introduction to Latin in LAT 101H1. Also appropriate for students who have some training in Latin, but have not completed a whole credit course at University or a final-year (Grade 12) course in secondary school.

LAT201H1-F-20169.courseDescription: Reading of selections of Latin prose works with systematic language study.
LAT201H1-F-20169.prerequisite: LAT100Y1/LAT102H1. Grade 12 in Latin may be accepted, but students should consult the Undergraduate Coordinator before enrolling.

LAT202H1-S-20169.courseDescription: Continued language training with readings in Latin prose and verse.

LAT340H1-F-20169.courseDescription: Readings from one or more Latin novelists.

LAT350H1-F-20169.courseDescription: Readings from one or more Latin epics, including Virgil.

LAT352H1-S-20169.courseDescription: Readings from one or more Latin satirists.

LAT428H1-F-20169.courseDescription: Independent Studies. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.
LAT428H1-F-20169.webTimetableInstructions: Applicants should first contact a potential supervisor for the proposed project. Once they have the supervisor's agreement, they should bring it to the Undergraduate Coordinator, Room 110, 125 Queen's Park or email undergrad.classics@utoronto.ca

LAT429H1-S-20169.courseDescription: Independent Studies. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.
LAT429H1-S-20169.webTimetableInstructions: Applicants should first contact a potential supervisor for the proposed project. Once they have the supervisor's agreement, they should bring it to the Undergraduate Coordinator, Room 110, 125 Queen's Park or email undergrad.classics@utoronto.ca

LAT430H1-F-20169.courseDescription: A course designed to enhance language skills. Prose composition, sight translation, stylistic analysis of Latin prose.

LAT440H1-F-20169.courseDescription: Advanced readings from one or more Latin novelists.

LAT442H1-S-20169.courseDescription: Advanced readings from Latin orators, including Cicero.

LAT450H1-F-20169.courseDescription: Advanced readings from one or more Latin epics, including Virgil.

LAT452H1-S-20169.courseDescription: Advanced readings from one or more Latin satirists.
